I understand that your initial hook for this game was drifting, but drifting is a lot harder than some people might let on. You need quite a bit of experience, understanding and the right car... ( Miata, chat? really!? MIATA?!?! Talk about being harsh on the newbie...) and so...

There is a track called the Nordschleife. It is around 20 Km (13 mi) long, has many bumps and elevation changes and the barriers are very close to the track, which means there isn't much room for error. Because of this, the people gave this circuit the nickname "Green Hell" as most of the track leads through a forrest.

With all that scary stuff out of the way, it would be awesome to see you finish a lap with the engine still running. (not because I don't believe in you, but because it is genuinly difficult)
Next step would probably be to get through without hitting any walls, and maybe get a lap time under 10 minutes.
(Other people will probably aggree with me when I say that Nordschleife is the most satisfying circuit to drive when you get it just right)

This will probably take you a long time, and chat might sometimes be a bit harsh, but remember that me, and I'm sure others from the European VOD gang, are cheering for you from the future, and awaiting the first coming of the HDK - Holo Drift King!

tip: the pedal on the left of the gas pedal is, despite popular belief, useful. :^)

actually useful tip: set up your FFB (Force FeedBack) right. This is very important because visual information is simply not enough. Especially when racing other people. There are many guides on the internet about this, so try some and see what fits. Just don't put the strength too high, your arms might get tired, or if worse comes to worst, you might hurt yourself.

text:
GURAAAAAA, fellow sim racer here. It's amazing to see Assetto Corsa being exposed to a different kind of audience! Although, if there are future streams of Assetto Corsa, I think the stuff below would be pretty useful. I hope Gura can notice this comment to make her Assetto Corsa experience even better. (like so Gura can see this/!?!)

Assetto Corsa is in this weird state where the modding community is keeping the game alive better than the actual developers. From the UI, it looks like Assetto Corsa was launched directly from Steam. I'm pretty sure other Assetto Corsa fans can agree that almost none of us uses the launcher from Steam. Instead, the modding community has created a much better launcher called Content Manager. This is pretty much the most important modification you can make to Assetto Corsa and it opens up a bunch of possibilities such as modding tens and thousands of cars and a bunch of tracks (meme cars included). Additionally, it makes the game look and run way better, which shouldn't be a problem with your insane PC.

The installation is pretty simple. Extract and set Assetto Corsa's game directory in Content Manager. From then on, Assetto Corsa can be launched from Content Manager instead. Even modding is as simple as a drag and drop into Content Manager. I don't think I can paste the link here or this comment would be flagged or something idk, but there are tons of tutorials out there. There is technically a paid version for Content Manager but that just supports the individuals who are making Assetto Corsa a better place and grants us early access to future improvements. The free version most people are using is sufficient enough. 

Looking forward to more racing streams in the future! (maybe BeamNg???)

text: If she's playing it just for fun and doesn't want to become a regular Assetto Corsa player then she doesn't need to learn anything but if she wants to play it more regular then it's not only being slow into the corners to be fast out of them, but also about the right braking point, the right turn in point, hitting the apex and the right acceleration (primary for slow corners). Copse in Silverstone is a good example. It's a fast corner in a F1 car and if you miss the turn in point you can't hit the apex and you lose time. Same with Maggots and Becketts. If you miss one apex the whole section is screwed and the lap as well. I lost up to 5 tenths when i screwed Copse and between 5 tenths and 2 seconds when i screwed Maggots and Becketts. An example for the right acceleration is Turn 1 at Spa. It has a bump at the apex where the rear of the car will get loose and if you get onto the power to early you will spin. Or the last corner at Spa which is off camber. Had many loose rear moments and spins there. Or the old Turn 11 in Catalunya (God i hate that corner).

text:
In the years that have passed since Darrell "Jaws" Waltrip's retirement from racing, no other driver could ever take the mantle of his Jaws moniker. But on this day in 2021, a little shark girl, Gawr Gura, has been recently playing sim racing games to see if she had what it took to be a racer. She humored the idea of joining NASCAR, but she grew to dislike how there was very little variety in the cars. But as she did further research on the history of the sanctioning body, the Modified Series caught her attention.

In the "Anything Goes" Era of the Modified Series, drivers could show up with whatever car they owned. It could be either some Ford V8 Coupe with no fenders, or a brand new Corvette with a souped-up engine. Not one entry was identical to the other. But that was all gone by the mid-80s. The era of uniformity had begun.

Whilst Gura was disappointed in the fact that there doesn't exist another league that was exactly like the Modified Series of old, she did come across an oval racing feature that did capture the essence of the old Modified Series: Spectator Drags. 1v1, road-legal cars (stock or modified), small ovals, full-on contact, 1 lap to prove who was the best.

With that knowledge, Gura started her journey to racecar driver on a computer. She knew exactly what car she wanted to bring to those events when the time came: A 1971 C3 Corvette. Deep down, Gura's dark side yearned to bump her opponents outta the way.

The new Jaws was born.
